				<text_box vertical_text_align="bottom" font_size="16pt" border_width="2" border_style="solid" uid="173" x="1751.67" y="27.6543" width="876.667" height="525.435">The roles of the Concrete Module are 
(1) to estimate the supply and demand of critical material resources required for the processes represented in the other modules, 
(2) to calculate the emissions resulting from these value chains, and 
(3) to simulate the effects of material bottle necks on these processes (e.g., material limitations to the energy transition).     

The production of concrete, and specifically cement which is the primary binding agent of concrete, is responsible for about 8% of annual anthropogenic CO2 emissions (REF). The Concrete module simulates the global production and in-use stock of concrete and associated CO2 emissions. Two types of uses are considered: concrete in housing and service buildings and concrete in infrastructure. These structures are divided up into two age categories each (‘New’ and ‘Old’) and as structures age they transition from ‘New’ to ‘Old’ until they reach their estimated service lifetime by which they are decommissioned. The demand for housing or infrastructure is assumed to be driven by population size and wealth (GDP per capita). As the population grows and/or get wealthier the demand for housing and infrastructure increases, which drives further construction and hence concrete production and associated emissions (87-164 kg CO2/ton of concrete depending on use-type). Additionally, in-use concrete structures deteriorate over time and require maintenance/repairs that also increase the global concrete production. The rate of deterioration increases and the average life time of concrete structures decreases with climate change, requiring more concrete to be produced to maintain the existing stocks, due to damages from extreme weather events (computed as a sub-fraction of asset storm damages in the Sea level rise Module) and enhanced corrosion (scaling with Surface Temperature Anomaly).

Primary information sources include:

Marinova et al (2019) : https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclepro.2019.119146
Deetman et al (2020) : https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclepro.2019.118658
F. Krausmann, et al (2017) : https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1613773114
USGS : https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nmic/historical-statistics-mineral-and-material-commodities-united-states.

Correspondence: andreas.nicolaidis@ri.se </text_box>
				<text_box font_weight="bold" text_align="center" font_size="28pt" appearance="transparent" uid="174" x="1985" y="50.6543" width="353.333" height="58">The Concrete Module</text_box>
